\begin_layout Section
Slope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Intro to slope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of steepness of a line can be defined by a nuber describing the
 speed at which it increases or decreses.
 To do this, we can look at how much a line 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

increses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the horizontal axis for a given horizontal axis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Resources/pasted1.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For every horizontal step, the line increases by two vertical steps.
 The magenta line thus has a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

steepness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{1}$
\end_inset

 which we call the slope.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If is devined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{slope}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Positive & negative slope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A line with a positive slope will see its 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 component increase as the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 component increases.
 A line with a negative slope will see its 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 component decrease as its 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 component increases.
\end_layout

